# Monitoring & Logging Documentation

## Overview
This project uses Prometheus + Grafana for metrics and Azure Monitor for logging.

## 1. Prometheus & Grafana Setup

### Install on AKS cluster:
```bash
helm repo add prometheus-community \
  https://prometheus-community.github.io/helm-charts

helm repo update

helm install monitoring \
  prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack \
  --namespace monitoring \
  --create-namespace \
  -f monitoring/prometheus-values.yaml
```

### Access Grafana:
```bash
# Get password
kubectl --namespace monitoring get secrets monitoring-grafana \
  -o jsonpath="{.data.admin-password}" | base64 -d ; echo

# Port forward
kubectl --namespace monitoring port-forward \
  svc/monitoring-grafana 3000:80
```

Then open: http://localhost:3000
- Username: admin
- Password: (from command above)

### What Prometheus scrapes:
- expensy-backend  → backend.default.svc.cluster.local:8706
- expensy-frontend → frontend.default.svc.cluster.local:3000
- All Kubernetes nodes and pods automatically

### Grafana Dashboards:
- Kubernetes / Compute Resources / Cluster → CPU, Memory
- Kubernetes / Compute Resources / Pod → per pod metrics
- Sample dashboard: monitoring/grafana-dashboard.json

## 2. Alertmanager
Alertmanager is included in kube-prometheus-stack.
It handles alerts fired by Prometheus.

### View alerts:
```bash
kubectl --namespace monitoring port-forward \
  svc/monitoring-kube-prometheus-alertmanager 9093
```
Then open: http://localhost:9093

## 3. Azure Monitor (Logging)

### Enable Container Insights:
```bash
az aks enable-addons \
  --resource-group nata-expensy-rg \
  --name nata-expensy-cluster \
  --addons monitoring
```

### View logs in Azure Portal:
1. Go to Azure Portal
2. Navigate to nata-expensy-rg
3. Click nata-expensy-cluster
4. Click "Logs" in left menu
5. Use KQL queries:

```kql
# View all container logs
ContainerLog
| where TimeGenerated > ago(1h)
| project TimeGenerated, ContainerName, LogEntry
| order by TimeGenerated desc

# View backend logs only
ContainerLog
| where ContainerName contains "backend"
| project TimeGenerated, LogEntry
| order by TimeGenerated desc

# View errors only
ContainerLog
| where LogEntry contains "error"
| project TimeGenerated, ContainerName, LogEntry
```

### View via kubectl:
```bash
# View backend logs
kubectl logs -l app=backend --tail=100

# View frontend logs
kubectl logs -l app=frontend --tail=100

# Stream live logs
kubectl logs -l app=backend -f
```

